A film by @type7

Son of legendary Australian shaper and surfer Neal Purchase, Neal Purchase Jnr was more or less born into the profession and culture. Growing up competing, Neal found his way as a free surfer, later following his father’s footsteps as a shaper. Now, Neal is renowned internationally for his surfing ability as well as his craftsmanship.

His iconic Duo, Quartet and Single fin shapes are a modern day homage to the past, something he credits to his father’s influence. An ever evolving refinement of classic designs, Neal’s boards are just as much a work of art as they are high performance surf craft. 

Yet despite his status in the surf world, 'Purcho' is one of the most kind, humble people you will meet. In fact, he scored the soundtrack for this very film 🏄‍♂️

Directed by @caplice
Starring @nealpurchasejnr
Production Company @mojaveproductions
Produced by @harrisonamark
Director Of Photography @andygough_

Special thanks to @lemac_australia & @filmstock_aust

Follow Anders’ journey as he works to meticulously restore a car he and his father worked on together in this beautiful video hosted on our channel from our friend @alex___schiller 🟡

node.text:
“Both are 1969, both a match for one another. I now have the perfect pair of machines to make every day commutes feel like a chase scene from a spy thriller.”

Steven Lindenfelser (@stevenlindenfelser) is an airhead to the core. For once, that’s not a pejorative. His garage, a 912 and a hand built @roughchild bike are the stuff of dreams. It’s rare you get a duo to match this well while ticking such a broad set of boxes.

“The 912 came first,” he explains. “I asked a dealer to look for one in any shade of green and they came through with a car in olive. It was a love at first sight moment. The interior had been fabulously restored, the only thing I added was a wood wheel. However, it didn’t run as well as it looked. It had some Dellorto carbs that I immediately swapped for Webers. The motor had a small leak in one side so I swapped to higher compression pistons when it was repaired. 912 legend John Benton (@bentonperformance) did all the work, now it’s a daily driver.”

Photos by @jrhebertphoto
Words by @therealalfiemunkenbeck for @type7

node.text:
Even though this 1965 911 was highly original, Jan (@janeguicosta) wanted it to have a few sporty touches, and immediately the @2litrecup racing series became an inspiration for him.

“I added a Monte Carlo Rollcage and exhaust, 6-inch wide wheels, deleted the trim on the front bumper and we painted the green line on the bonnet. I prefer the sporting look now without compromising much of its comfort. I still retains all the original wood in the interior, but to complete the feeling a pair of Heuer rally watches were added.”

It might have been moving for nearly 60 years already but Jan has no plans to stop enjoying it. Only time will tell if we will be seeing him and his 911 on the start line at a race soon.

node.text:
After driving through an unassuming but beautiful village on the edge of the Cotswolds you find yourself at @albion_barn, possibly the best art venue you've never heard of before. This exhibition and project space is currently showing their inaugural exhibition until the end of September in collaboration with a number of leading global galleries, and if this is a signal of what's to come we can't wait to see what else they come up with.

Upon entering you’re immediately faced with one of Erwin Wurm (@erwinwurm)’s Fat Car pieces. However, not everything in the grounds is as bombastic - John Pawson’s quiet works are featured here alongside a number of other reflective pieces which sit perfectly in their environment as benches or small monoliths. Possibly the most playful is artist Ai Weiwei (@aiww)’s marble sofa chair, placed in what could be the umpires position on a tennis court. 

Stepping away from the barn, you head into the aptly-named Albion Fields, a vast and private meadow and woodland containing a collection of pieces connected by small paths through the underbrush. On the day I was fortunate enough to visit I was only surrounded by wildlife; rabbits, butterflies and pheasants who call the grounds their home. Alongside the exhibiting pieces in the fields are two pavilions situated within glades of trees, from David Adjaye (@adjaye_visual_sketchbook) and Vito Acconci.

The entire venue feels like a best kept secret, and while we hope it keeps that feeling, we couldn’t help but share with you our thoughts and captures from the day, and needless to say, we’re already planning a return visit as the sculptures and installations will be replaced  biannually.

Photos and words by @nat_twiss for @type7

node.text:
You’re looking at one of the first 911s ever produced, a car that has travelled further than most people.

@janeguicosta’s 911 was sold new all the way back in 1965 in Santa Isabel, now known as Malabo, in Equatorial Guinea on the western coast of Africa. Shortly after the country became independent the car made its way to Canada, and then in the early 1970s it arrived on Catalan soil in Barcelona where it remains today.

Even now, Jan’s car still rides with its original Barcelona plates; “It wasn’t until 2000 that we bought this car to be part of the family collection,” Jan explains, now the fourth generation of owners of the Barcelona-based Juliá Porsche Specialist workshop. “Even today, it’s one of the cars me and my dad drive the most. We have no plans to sell, it’s definitely here to stay.”
